  "schema_version": 1.4,
  "sections": [
    {
      "name": "Waxen Effigy",
      "sections": [
        {
          "image": {
            "image": "Sidebar_2_AdditionalLore.png",
            "name": "Additional Lore",
            "type": "image"
          },
          "name": "Cruel Creations",
          "sidebar_heading": "Additional Lore",
          "sidebar_type": "additional_lore",
          "sources": [
            {
              "link": {
                "alt": "Pathfinder #205: Singer, Stalker, Skinsaw Man pg. 89",
                "aonid": 246,
                "game-obj": "Sources",
                "name": "Pathfinder #205: Singer, Stalker, Skinsaw Man pg. 89",
                "type": "link"
              },
              "name": "Pathfinder #205: Singer, Stalker, Skinsaw Man",
              "page": 89,
              "type": "source"
            }
          ],
          "subtype": "sidebar",
          "text": "Few set out to create a waxen effigy on purpose, as their fragmented memories cause them to behave rather erratically, and as such, they make poor guardians or assassins. Any intentional creation of a waxen effigy is solely an act of spite since it condemns the soul to an undeath steeped in bewilderment and fear.",
          "type": "section"
        }
      ],
      "sources": [
        {
          "link": {
            "alt": "Pathfinder #205: Singer, Stalker, Skinsaw Man pg. 89",
            "aonid": 246,
            "game-obj": "Sources",
            "name": "Pathfinder #205: Singer, Stalker, Skinsaw Man pg. 89",
            "type": "link"
          },
          "name": "Pathfinder #205: Singer, Stalker, Skinsaw Man",
          "page": 89,
          "type": "source"
        }
      ],
      "text": "The undead ooze known as a waxen effigy forms under a specific set of circumstances, making such creatures quite rare. Most waxen effigies arise from botched rituals intended to migrate a powerful sapient creature's soul into a body made of wax, whether in a bid for immortality or a method of imprisonment or sacrifice. The death\u2014especially a traumatic death\u2014of a sapient creature in close proximity to a wax figure or while attempting to craft a construct out of wax might also result in a waxen effigy.  \n  \n A waxen effigy looks like a partially melted wax version of who it appeared as in life. They retain little of their former personality but recall a jumble of memories from their mortal existence that serves only to anger them. They often cling to objects that were important to them in life, such as a spouse's wedding band or a tool from a favorite hobby. Displaying such an object to a waxen effigy transfixes their attention, though they often lash out if the object is taken away before they can be laid to rest.",
      "type": "section"
    }
  ],
  "sources": [
